```julia
abstract type AbstractVehicle end
struct Car <: AbstractVehicle end
struct Motorcycle <: AbstractVehicle end
struct Bus <: AbstractVehicle end
struct Truck <: AbstractVehicle end

function ispersonal(vehicle::AbstractVehicle)
    return vehicle isa Union{Car, Motorcycle}
end

# Examples
@show ispersonal(Car()) # true
@show ispersonal(Motorcycle()) # true
@show ispersonal(Bus()) # false
@show ispersonal(Truck()) # false
```

In the above code, we define an abstract type `AbstractVehicle` and four subtypes: `Car`, `Motorcycle`, `Bus`, and `Truck`. The `ispersonal` function takes a vehicle object as input and checks if it's an instance of either `Car` or `Motorcycle`, returning `true` if so, and `false` otherwise. The `@show` macro is used to display the output of the function calls for `Car()`, `Motorcycle()`, `Bus()`, and `Truck()`.
